GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 396
Short Title: Nursing Fellows & Curric. Support Funds/WSSU. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Lambeth, Potts, and White (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Appropriations, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 17, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH THE NURSING FELLOWS PROGRAM AT WINSTON-SALEM
3 STATE UNIVERSITY AND TO APPROPRIATE FUNDS FOR CURRICULUM
4 SUPPORT FOR NURSING STUDENTS AT WINSTON-SALEM STATE UNIVERSITY.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6
7 PART I. NURSING FELLOWS PROGRAM AT WINSTON-SALEM STATE
8 UNIVERSITY
9 SECTION 1.(a) Article 23 of Chapter 116 of the General Statutes is amended by
10 adding the following new Part to read:
11 "Part 3A. Nursing Fellows Program.
12 "§ 116-209.64. Definitions.
13 The following definitions apply in this Part:
14 (1) Academic term. – A semester or summer session.
15 (2) Authority. – The State Education Assistance Authority.
16 (3) Dean. – The Dean of the School of Health Sciences at WSSU.
17 (4) Eligible nurse. – A nurse who meets all of the following criteria:
18 a. Received a forgivable loan.
19 b. Graduated within 10 years from at least one of the following at WSSU,
20 excluding any authorized deferment for extenuating circumstances:
21 1. A Bachelor of Science in Nursing program.
22 2. A Master of Science in Nursing Education program.
23 c. Is licensed as a registered nurse in this State.
24 (5) Forgivable loan. – A forgivable loan made under the Program.
25 (6) Program. – The Nursing Fellows Program.
26 (7) Qualifying nurse. – An eligible nurse who meets all of the following criteria:
27 a. Holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Nursing from WSSU.
28 b. Is employed as a nurse in this State.
29 (8) Qualifying nurse instructor. – An eligible nurse who meets all of the following
30 criteria:
31 a. Holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Nursing from WSSU and a
32 Master of Science degree in Nursing Education from WSSU.
33 b. Is employed as an instructor in a qualifying nursing program.
*H396-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (9) Qualifying nursing program. – A nursing program at one of the following that
2 prepares students to earn a degree in nursing and become a licensed practical
3 nurse as defined in Article 9A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes:
4 a. A community college.
5 b. A university or private postsecondary institution.
6 (10) Trust Fund. – The Nursing Fellows Program Trust Fund.
7 (11) University or private postsecondary institution. – Either of the following:
8 a. A postsecondary constituent institution of The University of North
9 Carolina as defined in G.S. 116-2(4).
10 b. An eligible private postsecondary educational institution as defined in
11 G.S. 116-280(3).
12 (12) WSSU. – Winston-Salem State University.
13 "§ 116-209.65. North Carolina Nursing Fellows Program established; administration.
14 (a) Program. – There is established the Nursing Fellows Program. The purpose of the
15 Program is to recruit, prepare, and support eligible nursing students at WSSU for preparation as
16 highly effective nurses and instructors in qualifying nursing programs. The Program shall be used
17 to provide forgivable loans to nursing students who are (i) enrolled in degree programs at WSSU
18 to receive a Bachelor of Science in Nursing or a Master of Science in Nursing Education and (ii)
19 interested in preparing to become nurses in the State or instructors in qualifying nursing
20 programs.
21 (b) Program Administration; Dean. – The Authority shall administer the Program in
22 cooperation with the Dean. The Dean shall determine forgivable loan recipient selection criteria
23 and selection procedures and shall select the recipients to receive forgivable loans under the
24 Program in accordance with the requirements of this Part. The Dean shall appoint any needed
25 staff of the Program and shall be responsible for recruitment and coordination of the Program,
26 including proactive, aggressive, and strategic recruitment of potential recipients. Recruitment
27 activities shall include (i) targeting regions of the State with the greatest need for nurses and
28 nursing instructors in qualifying nursing programs, (ii) actively engaging with registered nurses,
29 business leaders, experts in human resources, elected officials, and other community leaders
30 throughout the State, and (iii) attracting candidates to the Program. WSSU shall provide office
31 space and clerical support staff, as necessary, to the Dean for the Program.
32 (c) Trust Fund. – There is established the Nursing Fellows Program Trust Fund to be
33 administered by the Authority, in conjunction with the Dean. All funds (i) appropriated to, or
34 otherwise received by, the Program for forgivable loans and other Program purposes, (ii) received
35 as repayment of forgivable loans, and (iii) earned as interest on these funds shall be placed in the
36 Trust Fund. The purpose of the Trust Fund is to provide financial assistance to qualified students
37 to fill needed positions for nurses in the State and instructors in qualifying nursing programs
38 through completion of a Bachelor of Science degree in Nursing or both a Bachelor of Science
39 degree in Nursing and a Master of Science degree in Nursing Education.
40 (d) Uses of Monies in the Trust Fund. – The monies in the Trust Fund may be used only
41 for (i) forgivable loans granted under the Program, (ii) administrative costs associated with the
42 Program, including recruitment and recovery of funds advanced under the Program, (iii)
43 mentoring and coaching support to forgivable loan recipients, and (iv) extracurricular
44 enhancement activities of the Program in accordance with the following:
45 (1) The Authority shall transfer six percent (6%) of the available funds from the
46 Trust Fund to WSSU at the beginning of each fiscal year for the following
47 purposes:
48 a. The Program's administrative costs.
49 b. Extracurricular enhancement activities of the Program.
Page 2 House Bill 396-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Mentoring and coaching support to forgivable loan recipients in an
2 amount of up to two thousand two hundred dollars ($2,200) for each
3 Program recipient.
4 (2) The Authority may use up to four percent (4%) of the funds appropriated to
5 the Trust Fund each fiscal year for administrative costs associated with the
6 Program.
7 (e) Student Selection Criteria for Forgivable Loans. – The Dean, in consultation with the
8 Associate Dean of Nursing at WSSU, shall adopt stringent standards for awarding forgivable
9 loans based on multiple measures to ensure that only the strongest applicants receive them,
10 including the following:
11 (1) Grade point averages.
12 (2) Performance on relevant assessments.
13 (3) Experience, accomplishments, and other criteria demonstrating qualities
14 positively correlated with highly effective nurses and instructors in qualifying
15 nursing programs, including excellent verbal and communication skills.
16 (4) Demonstrated commitment to serve in North Carolina.
17 (f) Awards of Forgivable Loans. – The Program shall provide forgivable loans to selected
18 students who are initially enrolled in a Bachelor of Science in Nursing degree program at WSSU.
19 Loan payments shall be provided each year for completion of the Bachelor of Science in Nursing
20 program and, if a loan recipient seeks to become a qualifying nurse instructor, for a Master of
21 Science in Nursing Education program. The student shall be eligible to receive loan payments
22 for the Master of Science in Nursing Education program as long as the student enrolls within two
23 years of graduation from the Bachelor of Science in Nursing program. Forgivable loans may be
24 used for tuition, fees, the cost of books, and expenses related to completing a Bachelor of Science
25 degree in Nursing and a Master of Science degree in Nursing Education. Forgivable loans shall
26 be awarded per academic term in amounts of up to five thousand dollars ($5,000) per semester
27 or two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500) per summer session, as follows:
28 (1) For students pursuing careers as qualifying nurses, for up to five semesters.
29 (2) For persons pursuing careers as qualifying nurse instructors, for up to nine
30 semesters.
31 (g) Administration of Forgivable Loan Awards. – Upon the naming of recipients of the
32 forgivable loans by the Dean, the Dean shall transfer to the Authority its decisions. The Authority,
33 in coordination with the Dean, shall perform all of the administrative functions necessary to
34 implement this Part, which functions shall include rulemaking, disseminating information, acting
35 as a liaison with participating institutions of higher education, implementing forgivable loan
36 agreements, loan monitoring, loan canceling through service and collection, determining the
37 acceptability of service repayment agreements, enforcing the agreements, and all other functions
38 necessary for the execution, payment, and enforcement of promissory notes required under this
39 Part.
40 (h) Annual Report. – The Dean, in coordination with the Authority, shall report no later
41 than January 1, 2027, and annually thereafter, to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight
42 Committee regarding the following:
43 (1) Forgivable loans awarded from the Trust Fund, including the following:
44 a. Demographic information regarding recipients.
45 b. Number of recipients by institution of higher education.
46 (2) Placement and repayment rates, including the following:
47 a. Number of graduates who have been employed as qualifying nurses in
48 the State and qualifying nurse instructors in qualifying nursing
49 programs within two years of graduation.
50 b. Number of graduates who have elected to do loan repayment and their
51 years of service, if any, prior to beginning loan repayment.
