11 "§ 116-209.66. Terms of forgivable loans; receipt and disbursement of funds.
12 (a) Notes. – All forgivable loans shall be evidenced by notes made payable to the
13 Authority that bear interest at a rate not to exceed ten percent (10%) per year as set by the
14 Authority and beginning on the first day of September after completion of the applicable degree
15 program or 90 days after graduation, whichever is later. If a forgivable loan is terminated, the
16 note shall be made payable to the Authority 90 days after termination of the forgivable loan. The
17 forgivable loan may be terminated upon the recipient's withdrawal from the Program or by the
18 recipient's failure to meet the standards set by the Dean.
19 (b) Forgiveness. – For every year a qualifying nurse remains a qualifying nurse or a
20 qualifying nurse instructor remains a qualifying nurse instructor, the Authority shall forgive
21 one-third of the total loan amount received over the course of enrollment in the applicable degree
22 program and any interest accrued on that amount. The Authority shall also forgive the loan if it
23 finds that it is impossible for the recipient to work for up to three years, within 10 years after
24 completion of the Bachelor of Science in Nursing degree program for persons pursuing
25 forgiveness as qualifying nurses or of the Master of Science in Nursing Education degree
26 program for persons pursuing forgiveness as qualifying nurse instructors, because of the death or
27 permanent disability of the recipient. If the recipient repays the forgivable loan by cash payments,
28 all indebtedness shall be repaid within 10 years after completion of the latest applicable degree
29 program supported by the forgivable loan. If the recipient completes the applicable degree
30 program, payment of principal and interest shall begin no later than the first day of September
31 after the completion of the program. Should a recipient present extenuating circumstances, the
32 Authority may extend the period to repay the loan in cash to no more than a total of 12 years."
